04822nam a2200601Ia 9780292758995DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20131986txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927589957 a10.7560/7075972doi  a(DE-B1597)587588  a(OCoLC)1280944070  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a522.197649341 aEvans, David S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBig and Bright :bA History of the McDonald Observatory /cJ. Derral Mulholland, David S. Evans. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©1986  a1 online resource (226 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory of Science Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Tourist's Observatory -- t2. The Benefactor -- t3. The Legal Contests -- t4. The Texas-Chicago Agreement -- t5. Choosing and Developing the Site -- t6. A Mosque on Mount Locke -- t7. Astronomy Comes to West Texas -- t8. Mr. McDonald's Telescope -- t9. The Dedication -- t10. War Years, Struve Years -- t11. Triumphs and Transitions -- t12. Interregnum -- t13. Texas Independence -- t14. Launching the Modern Era -- tEpilogue -- tAPPENDIX A The Last Will and Testament of William Johnson McDonald -- tAPPENDIX B The Directors of the McDonald Observatory -- tAPPENDIX C The Telescopes of the University of Texas Observatories -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy day, every year over 40,000 visitors pour in. Across the Rio Grande, a hundred miles away, Mexican mountaineers use the white domes as landmarks. By night, perched almost 7,000 feet above the sleeping, earthbound world, astronomers probe the secrets of the night sky. This is the University of Texas McDonald Observatory, one of the world's largest university-operated astronomical installations. Big and Bright: A History of the McDonald Observatory is the story of a remarkable collaboration between two major universities, one a prestigious private school, the other a growing southwestern state institution. The University of Chicago had astronomers, but its Yerkes Observatory was aging and underfunded; the University of Texas had money for an observatory but no working astronomer to staff it. Out of their mutual need, they formed a thirty-year compact for a joint venture. Unusual in its day, the Yerkes-McDonald connection presaged the future. In this arrangement, one can see some of the beginnings of today's consortium "big science." Now the McDonald Observatory's early history can be put in proper perspective. Blessed with a gifted and driving founding director, the world's (then) second-largest telescope, and an isolation that permitted it to be virtually the only major astronomical observatory that continued operations throughout World War II, the staff of McDonald Observatory helped lay the foundations of modern astrophysics during the 1940s. For over a decade after the war, a lonely mountaintop in West Texas was the mecca that drew nearly all the most important astronomers from all over the world. Based on personal reminiscences and archival material, as well as published historical sources, Big and Bright is one of the few histories of a major observatory, unique in its focus on the human side of the story.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aMulholland, J. Derral, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311074535140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70759740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292758995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292758995/original  a978-3-11